        <div class="faq-list">
                    <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What is the HSA contribution limit for 2026?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">The projected 2026 HSA contribution limit is approximately $4,400 for self-only HDHP coverage and $8,750 for family coverage. These are projections; the IRS confirms official figures in a Revenue Procedure typically released in May of the prior year. Account holders 55 and older can contribute an additional $1,000.</div>
          </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Can I still contribute to an HSA for 2025?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">If you had HDHP coverage in 2025, you can contribute up to the 2025 limit ($4,300 self-only / $8,550 family) up until April 15, 2026 &mdash; the tax filing deadline. Contributions made before the deadline and designated for 2025 are deductible on your 2025 return.</div>
          </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What happens to unused HSA funds?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Unlike FSAs, HSA funds roll over year after year with no use-it-or-lose-it rule. The balance is yours permanently. You can invest it, let it grow tax-free, and use it in future years or in retirement. There is no deadline to spend HSA funds.</div>
          </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Can both spouses have HSAs in 2026?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Yes, but only if both have their own HDHP coverage. If both spouses have self-only HDHP plans, each can contribute up to the self-only limit to their individual HSAs (~$4,400 each projected for 2026). If one has a family HDHP plan that covers both, the combined contribution cap is the family limit (~$8,750), split however you choose between the two accounts.</div>
          </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Is the HSA catch-up contribution limit changing for 2026?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">No. The $1,000 catch-up contribution for account holders 55 and older is set by statute and does not adjust for inflation. It has been $1,000 since 2009.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

